repo.description: The most widely used Python to C compiler
repo.name: cython

body:
Allow ctuples as return type of optimised builtins and use it for `divmod()` of C integers.

Also make sure that we prefer function signatures with wider numeric types over those with narrower types if there are multiple alternatives. This helps when calling functions with mixed integer types (e.g. arguments `int, long` should call a function with `long, long` rather than `int, int`).

Supersedes and closes https://github.com/cython/cython/pull/6520

comment_data.body: I haven't yet looked in detail at the rest of the PR, but while you're doing this it might be possible to remove this file from `limited_api_bugs.txt`. I think it was only the include for the C `div` function that's missing, so if you've removed that it'll probably just work.

commit.message: Allow ctuples as return type of optimised builtins and use it for divmod() of C integers.
Fix tuple tests after allowing to infer more ctuple types.
Allow disabling tree assertions in tests to force C code generation despite tree path failures.
When matching call signatures, prefer wider numeric types over narrower types.
Disable type inference for ctuples again. There are cases where this is not safe.
Allow 'or' in TreePath expressions. Simplify the predicate implementation.
Restructure the C utility code to simplify the conditions.
Remove type inference change that doesn't currently help and breaks tests.

milestone.description:
* Remove code for Python 2 and Python < 3.8.
* Integrate better with Python 3.
* Improve support for the Limited API.
* Start supporting GIL-free Python 3.13.
* Support the Py3.13 `sys.monitoring` API.
* Support and use `am_send` for coroutines.

title: Optimise divmod() for all C integer types
